{"id":"physics/0601095","submitter":"Yuri A. Rylov","authors":"Yuri A. Rylov","title":"On strategy of relativistic quantum theory construction","comments":"27 pages, 1 figure, v2 correction of misprints","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.gen-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  Two different strategies of the relativistic quantum theory construction are\nconsidered and evaluated. The first strategy is the conventional strategy,\nbased on application of the quantum mechanics technique to relativistic\nsystems. This approach cannot solve the problem of pair production. The\napparent success of QFT at solution of this problem is conditioned by the\ninconsistency of QFT, when the commutation relations are incompatible with the\ndynamic equations. (The inconsistent theory \"can solve\" practically any\nproblem, including the problem of pair production). The second strategy is\nbased on application of fundamental principles of classical dynamics and those\nof statistical description to relativistic dynamic systems. It seems to be more\nreliable, because this strategy does not use quantum principles, and the main\nproblem of QFT (join of nonrelativistic quantum principles with the principles\nof relativity) appears to be eliminated.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 13 Jan 2006 09:35:48 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 16 Jan 2006 08:46:58 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
